The Idolaters of Free Trade
From Cambridge — — Recently, I was invited to guest lecture in a globalization course taught by two of my Harvard colleagues. "I must warn you."
One of them事先 warned me: "These students are strong supporters of globalization."
He had asked the students in the first class to choose between free trade and import restrictions, and over 90% favored the former.
And this was before he had even begun to teach the magical effects of comparative advantage.
We know that using the same questions to ask representative samples — rather than Harvard students — in real investigations would yield a completely different result.
In the United States, the ratio of opponents to supporters of trade restrictions is 2:1.
But the answers of Harvard students would not be particularly surprising.
Because people with higher technology and better education tend to be more inclined to support free trade than blue-collar workers.
And perhaps these Harvard students have already anticipated their future (financial) prospects and made decisions accordingly.
Or perhaps, they actually don't understand how trade works.
After all, when I met with them, I deliberately rephrased the same question in a different form and emphasized the distributional effects that trade could generate.
The consensus supporting fair trade completely disappeared, even more quickly than I had anticipated.
At the beginning, I first asked everyone whether they agreed with me on a particularly magical experiment.
I selected Nicholas and John as volunteers and then told them that I had a way to make Nicholas's account's $200 disappear — poof! — while increasing John's account by $300, and through the wonders of social engineering, this class as a whole would gain an extra $100 in value.
Then would they allow me to pull this little trick?
As a result, only a small portion firmly agreed, many were hesitant, and even more opposed the implementation of this change.

It is obvious that students find it difficult to tolerate this form of large-scale income redistribution, even when the overall economic pie has been significantly increased.
I then asked why the majority of them almost instinctively support free trade, which actually also leads to a similar — in fact, even a larger — redistribution of wealth from losers to winners.
The students all looked stunned.
I then said, let's assume that Nicholas and John both opened competing small companies.
John worked harder, saved and invested more, and produced a better product, so he not only earned $300 more than Nicholas, but also drove Nicholas's company out of the market, causing him a loss of $200.
How many students then supported this change?
This time, most of them voted in favor — in fact, only Nicholas disagreed!
I then proposed another hypothesis directly related to international trade.
Could it be that John is pushing Nicholas out of the market by importing high-quality products from Germany?
Or by outsourcing business processes to China, where labor rights are not yet fully established?
Or by employing child labor in Indonesia?
This time, the level of approval for the change decreased sequentially with the above options.
Moreover, technological innovation can also, like trade, leave certain groups in a more disadvantaged position. What is your view on this?
Very few students are willing to restrain technological development in response to this.
To almost everyone, it would be a foolish idea to ban the production of light bulbs in order to preserve the jobs of candle makers.
Therefore, the students are not necessarily opposed to redistribution, but only to certain specific forms of redistribution.
Like most of us, they are concerned about the fairness of the process.
If we are to make a judgment about the outcome of redistribution, we must know the objective circumstances that produced such results.
We would not be resentful of Bill Gates or Warren Buffett's enormous wealth, even if some of their opponents have had difficult times, which is probably because they and their competitors all operate according to the same basic laws and face very similar opportunities and challenges.
However, if Gates and Buffett had become wealthy not through their own intelligence and efforts, but through fraud, violation of labor laws, environmental destruction, or by exploiting subsidies from foreign governments, our views would be completely different.
If we cannot tolerate redistribution achieved through the violation of widely observed moral standards domestically, how can we feel at ease simply because it involves cross-border transactions?
Similarly, when we expect the effects of redistribution to equalize in the long term, and everyone will ultimately benefit from it, we are likely to not care about the transfer of income.
This is why we believe that even though technology may bring about short-term negative responses for some people, we still remain willing to promote its development.
On the other hand, when trade continuously impacts the same group of people —— low-educated blue-collar workers —— we become concerned about globalization.
However, many economists ignore these obvious differences.
They tend to attribute concerns about globalization to foolish and selfish protectionist motives or ignorance, without realizing that the most important issue is actually a moral one.
Because they fail to recognize that international trade —— although not often —— sometimes leads to redistribution consequences that we would not accept domestically, these economists are also unable to properly engage in public discussions.
And if they are not even morally defensible, how can they strongly defend trade?
When globalization occasionally raises a thorny issue related to the legitimization of redistribution effects, we should not reflexively respond with trade restrictions.
There are still many pros and cons that require difficult balancing, including the possibility that globalization may cause more severe wealth deprivation for people in other places than for the victims in the United States itself.
However, democratic countries should have a more appropriate discussion on this and make conscious and more thoughtful decisions.
But the practice of being infatuated with globalization merely because it has made the cake bigger will inevitably corrode the legitimacy of globalization itself in the long run.
